{"action_ids":["1369","1370","906"],"query":"What are the most beneficial tillage practices for increasing soil organic matter in arable fields on Mediterranean farmland?","summary":"A meta-analysis of studies from Mediterranean countries revealed that soils without tillage had higher organic matter content compared to tilled soils (1369). Further supporting this, fourteen replicated studies in Italy, Spain, and the USA indicated that soils without tillage, in some or all comparisons, had more organic matter (1369). When specifically comparing no-tillage to reduced tillage in Spain, three replicated, randomized, controlled studies showed increased organic matter in no-tillage soils, while three other similar studies found no significant difference (1370). No studies in this comparison found less organic matter with no-tillage (1370).

Eight studies, including some in Morocco, observed that reduced tillage either maintained or increased soil organic matter (906). Additionally, twelve studies in various locations, including Spain, found higher soil organic carbon under no-tillage or reduced tillage systems compared to conventional tillage (906). One study in Spain also highlighted that soils that had not been tilled for a longer duration had more organic matter in one comparison (1369).

However, some studies present contrasting findings. One replicated, randomized, controlled study in Portugal reported less organic matter in soils without tillage in some comparisons (1369), and another in Spain showed mixed results (1369). Similarly, one randomized, replicated trial from Spain found greater soil organic carbon in conventionally tilled soil (906)."}

